message.content:
The start symbol is  

S → NT12 NT4  

so the string has to split into two consecutive substrings, the left one generated by NT12 and the right one by NT4.

1.  NT12 is extremely powerful:
    • It can produce a single terminal directly
      (e.g. NT12 → 't89', 't139', …).
    • It can expand to NT13 NT11.  
      NT13 and NT11 together cover terminals such as  
      t32, t53, t205, t216, t70, t78, t89, t183 … – all of which
      occur in the given string.
    • It can expand to NT12 NT0.  
      NT0 is recursive (NT0 → NT0 NT0) and
      has many single‑terminal rules
      (t127, t177, t185, t69, t55, t178, t114, t154 …).  
      Because the recursion is unrestricted, NT0 – and therefore NT12 –
      can contribute arbitrarily many occurrences of any of those terminals
      at any positions inside the NT12‑substring.
    • It can expand to NT4 NT4, and NT4 in turn can reach all of the
      non‑terminals NT5, NT7, NT8, NT11, NT12 again, …
      This places every terminal that any non‑terminal of the grammar
      can produce inside the scope of NT12.

   Thanks to these mutually recursive rules, NT12 can generate an
   arbitrary non‑empty sequence whose symbols are taken from the full
   terminal alphabet of the grammar.

2.  NT4 is just as expressive:
    • It has many direct terminal rules (t36, t104, t150, t156, t163,
      t169, t190, …).
    • It can expand to NT4 NT5, NT5 NT12, or NT11 NT8.
      Through NT5 (which uses NT7 and NT13), NT11, and NT8 (which
      reaches NT6, NT1, …) every terminal occurring anywhere in the
      grammar is again reachable inside NT4.
    • With the self‑embedding rule NT4 → NT4 NT5 it can iterate
      indefinitely, so it can produce sequences of any positive length.

3.  Coverage of the required terminals  
   Every one of the 40 terminals in the target string occurs in at least
   one single‑terminal rule of the grammar:

   t140 (NT7/NT9), t162 (NT6), t145 (NT8/NT2), t203 (NT1/NT6),
   t127 (NT0), t205 (NT13/NT8/NT6), t45 (NT1),
   t30 (NT5), t55 (NT0/NT1), t86 (NT5), t104 (NT4),
   t47 (NT6), t178 (NT0/NT1), t167 (NT2), t53 (NT6/NT13),
   t32 (NT13), t73 (NT5), t187 (NT0/NT1/NT8), t89 (NT12/NT5/NT13/NT9),
   t169 (NT4), t190 (NT4/NT12/NT2), t216 (NT11),
   t196 (NT9/NT10), t183 (NT13), t78 (NT11/NT3),
   t141 (NT1), t80 (NT3), t67 (NT5), t180 (NT1),
   t96 (NT9/NT10), t36 (NT4/NT10), t193 (NT7),
   t70 (NT11), t91 (NT8).

4.  Building the required 40‑symbol sentence  
   Because both NT12 and NT4 can generate sequences of arbitrary length
   that may contain every terminal symbol of the grammar,
   we can partition the 40‑token string at any position k (1 ≤ k ≤ 39),
   have NT12 derive the first k tokens and NT4 derive the remaining
   40 − k tokens.  
   The self‑embedding rules of NT12 and NT4 let us adjust their lengths
   freely, and the reachability arguments above guarantee that each of
   them can realise exactly the required terminals in the required order.

Since such a derivation exists, the given string belongs to the language
generated by the grammar.

Yes
